				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Combat Agility -v- Combat Stability<a name="37099"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 28 04 3:54 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Mitigation occurs in direct proportion to the ratio of mobs attack rating to your AC.  Now, increasing mitigation, like in CS and ID, will improve your chances of mitigating a max hit down to something else.  But that will be offset the higher the attack rating of the mob beating on you.  That means that against a boss with a really high attack, like AOW, your chances of mitigating a max hit down to something lower is not nearly as good as it would be on one of the normal arena giants.  Avoidance, on the other hand, is an increased probability of parrying, dodging, or blocking a hit and taking zero damage.  So even for warriors, avoidance is better to have than stability.  But for warriors, who have higher chances if mitigating damage than other melees anyway, they're already taking less damage per hit than an SK or a bard, for example.  In my normal experience group, we have a warrior and me as the only potential tanks.  We have very similar AC (I have darned good AC for a non-elemental, non-VT bard) but she takes MUCH less damage per hit, and that is with very similar defensive AAs.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
