				<td colspan="2"><span>Not parsing but sorta some math from the guide AA lists.
<br />

<br />
If a mob hits for XXXX damage.
<br />
10 hits with CS 3 is = 1 hit with CA 3
<br />
That means that someone who has CS 3 needs to get hit 10 times to make up for 1 &quot;proc&quot; of CA 3.  
<br />

<br />
The thing it really comes down to at 65 is hitpoint base.  For a good warrior with 10,000+ hp to work with, CS line gives a larger amount of mitigation over the course of their life.  For example:
<br />

<br />
A Mob hits for 1000 points of damage 11 times in 3 rounds.  Totaling 11,000 damage.  Not including AC or innate abilities such as dodge/parry/etc.
<br />
The unaltered warrior (meaning no AA defenses) gets hit for 11,000 damage and dies
<br />
The warrior with CS 3 gets hit for 9,900 damage and lives.
<br />
The warrior with CA 3 &quot;procs&quot; 1 time and gets hit for 10,000 damage and dies
<br />
The warrior with CA 3 &quot;procs&quot; 2+ times and gets hit for &lt;9,000 damage and lives.
<br />

<br />
In this scenario, the warrior is better off taking CS 3 because it has a greater reliability over time with a large HP base.
<br />

<br />
However, Bards do not have this large HP base to work with, even the best time flagged bards will probably only reach around 8500 fully buffed.  Under the same scenario:
<br />

<br />
Unaltered Bard gets hit for 11,000 and dies.
<br />
CS 3 Bard gets hit for 9,900 damage and dies.
<br />
CS 3 Bard &quot;procs&quot; 1 time and gets hit for 10,000 damage and dies.
<br />
CA 3 Bard &quot;procs&quot; 3+ times and gets hit for 8,000 damage and lives.
<br />

<br />
Although not reliable, Combat Agility offers the only chance of survival in this situation.  Hopefully as a bard, you'll be getting hit less, and in that case, one &quot;proc&quot; of CA 3 would allow you to mitigate the damage of ten CS 3 hits, and if you're getting hit ten times, you probably wouldn't live anyway.
<br />

<br />
And if you factor in what Xandrias said,
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">The damage you take is reduce slightly overall and the distribution of hits is evened out which makes healing more predictable.  Instead of taking 30% hits for max, 45% for minimum (dark blue Velious mobs this) and the rest in between since CS I have seen a distribution of 28% hits for max, 40% hits for minimum (hum) and the rest in between with a very even spread.</span></blockquote>
<br />
That means that CS isn't even as good as this math shows, again pointing to how much better CA/LR really is.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Feydrioron of Rodcet Nife</span></td>
